Data Science Milestone 2¶

Our group will consist of Luke Albright and James Manzer for the data science project and presentation. We are exploring historical Major League Baseball statistics to determine what variables correlate with the number of wins a team has during a season, as well as their predictive power for determining the number of wins a MLB team would have.

Collaboration Plan¶

We are roommates which makes collaboration throughout this project much easier. We plan to store any pertinent data and code through GitHub and Google CoLab. Our schedules align best on Monday and Wednesdays (as well as weekends) which is when we plan to complete any necessary meetings or collaborative work. However, noting again that we are roommates, we expect our schedule to be much more fluid. Our GitHub site hosting our data can be found at this link: https://github.com/lalbright22/lalbright22.github.io.git

Datasets:¶

The dataset we are interested in studying involves Major League Baseball statistics. Both of us have a history of playing baseball and are now fans of the Chicago Cubs and Texas Rangers. James is even a member of the club baseball team here at Tulane. Given our passion for baseball and its vast records of statistics, we feel compelled to take a deep exploration into a number of possible variables.

We have identified two websites in the public domain that store a trove of information pertaining to the MLB. The two sites are the Lahman Database and Retrosheet (links to both are included below). The Lahman Database has data such as pitching, hitting, fielding, salary data, and more from 1871 to the 2022 season. Retrosheet has data covering play-by-play, team statistics, and even a few unique datasets such as ejections. Retrosheet data typically spans from 1913 to the 2022 season.

There are many variables to explore but a preliminary idea was to investigate the keys of success for a team. One example would be to compare the total amount a team spends on player salaries and total wins for that season. This would test the theory of "spend money to make money," or in this case, to win games.

For this stage of our analysis, we will be pulling data from the Lahman database, which has multiple folders. These include "core" statistics such as players, parks, teams, batting, fielding, and more, as well as "contribution" statistics such as awards, salaries, college, and hall of fame information. Our milestone 2 will consist of a small sample of these files: teams, and salary.

Helpful Glossary¶

  • yearID = Year
  • lgID = League (National or American)
  • teamID = Team
  • franchID = Franchise
  • divID = Division
  • Rank = Ranking
  • G = Games
  • Ghome = Home Games
  • W = Wins
  • L = Loses
  • DivWin = Divisional Wins
  • WCWin = Wild Card Wins
  • LGWin = League Wins
  • WSWin = World Series Wins
  • R = Runs
  • AB = At Bats
  • H = Hits
  • 2B = Doubles
  • 3B = Triples
  • HR = Home Runs
  • BB = Walks
  • SO = Strike Outs
  • SB = Stolen Bases
  • CS = Caught Stealing
  • HBP = Hit by Pitch
  • SF = Sacrifice Fly
  • RA = Runs Against
  • ER = Earned Runs
  • ERA = Earned Runs Against
  • CG = Complete Game
  • SHO = Shutout
  • SV = Save
  • IPouts = Outs Pitched
  • HA = Hits Allowed
  • HRA = Home Runs Allowed
  • BBA = Walks Allowed
  • SOA = Strike Outs Allowed
  • E = Errors
  • DP = Double Play
  • FP = Fielding Percentage
  • name = Team Name
  • park = Ballpark
  • attendance = Attendance
  • BPF = Batting Park Factor
  • PPF = Pitching Park Factor

We chose to run linear regressions on pairs of variables with the dependent variable being wins in order to see if there is a strong correlation between any specific independent variable and the dependent variable. While we do see trends, there is no statistically significant correlation between wins and any of the other independent variables.

Model Questions¶

Looking forward, we came up with two models that we can build using our robust datasets to continue our investigation into what variables affect or are able to predict a MLB team's number of wins.

We want to run a ridge regression model on the dataset as a continuation of our linear regressions in order to elimnate extraneous coefficients from the model. The penalties for the factor coefficients will not only minimize the error of the model but minimize the size of the model. This would be helpful given our large dataset, as regular linear regression runs the risk of being a very large model. Also, we can incorperate train test splits in order to look for predictive power instead of correlation as has been done so far.

The second model we want to run our dataset would be a K-Nearest Neighbor model. Because many sucessful baseball teams have similar characteristics, we think that this model would be helpful in predicting the number of wins a team might have given independent variables. Also, we can analyze how changing K will affect the accuracy of the model, adding another dimension to our analysis.

With both models, we will also incorperate cross validation in order to further minimize overfitting, as this is a significant concern with any model. We will use sklearn moving forward to implement these models, and we will use error metrics such as MAE, MSE, and MAPE to analyze how these models perform when given new data.
